<div id="introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>Introduction</h1>
<p>The Bioconductor community survey was conducted via google forms during October - December 2019. It consisted of 40 questions about the usability, uptake and contributions of the Bioconductor project. By the end of the survey there were 117 respondents.</p>
<div id="demographics-of-respondents" class="section level2">
<h2>Demographics of respondents</h2>
<div id="gender" class="section level3">
<h3>Gender</h3>
<p>Responses to the gender question were given as free text, these have been recoded to broad categories using the <a href="https://github.com/ropenscilabs/gendercoder">gendercodeR</a> package.</p>

<div id="career-stage" class="section level3">
<h3>Career stage</h3>
<p>Responses to the career stage and position question were recoded into five broad categories:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>student: representing undergraduate / graduate students</li>
<li>postdoc: representing postdocs in academia or industry</li>
<li>academic: representing professors (assistant, full or emeritus), tenure track or PIs in academia</li>
<li>service: representing staff scientitsts, research assistants or bioinformaticians in academia or industry</li>
<li>other: any remaining career classification that are ambiguous like ‘industry’</li>
</ol>

<div id="mflkytmvzy" style="overflow-x:auto;overflow-y:auto;width:auto;height:auto;"><table class="gt_table">
  
  <tr>
    <th class="gt_col_heading gt_columns_bottom_border gt_columns_top_border gt_left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">What barriers are there to contributing your package to Bioconductor?</th>
  </tr>
  <body class="gt_table_body">
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Review time</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Time to tidy-up the scripts, optimize and submit.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Most of my packages are attached to a specific analysis project; they are too throwaway for release on bioconductor.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">I'm not well versed enough in S4 OOP, c++ and Bioconductor conventions to make classes and functions that play nice with other Bioconductor packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Including bash commands in vignettes. The bash commands are part of the workflow, though not required to use my R package. So I built a stand alone website just for vignettes that include the command line part of the workflow.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The requirement for creating the PDF Reference Manual. It is simply to easy to make something that makes this process brea.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">For a first time developer, information required to successfully develop and submit a package is very scattered. It would be great to have a single document that shows a step-wise workflow of how to develop and submit a Bioconductor package.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The review times can be extensive, and the enforced coding guidelines, although very much appreciated, do not always seem to be a must.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Collaborators (and I) don't like what using bioconductor packages does to your namespace</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Inaccessible resource to understand S4.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">no barriers, work incomplete at this point</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Career incentives, obscure bioc package requirements</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I'd like to see the packages hosted on GitHub rather than a separate git server. This would make it easer on the developer side to maintain the package. The example that comes to mind is ROpenSci.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">patchy documentation/tutorials of git versioning (esp. how to prevent big files from occuring in the first place). Guidelines that are clear BEFORE bioCcheck, not after, specialized functions, as in devtools, to check specific check item (e.g. like check_man). It's not clear whether one should contribute to existing package or develop their own.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">the workflow of submitting a package is not very straight forward and the response time in the submission forum could take up to more that 2 weeks, which makes progress slow</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">mostly the code styling</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">whether it's good/useful enough to be there</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Lack of programming knowledge + domain specific knowledge</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">It's a personal package, not suitable for BioC inclusion</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">When the submission deadline comes around I always find myself too busy. When we are in an “off cycle” release (when devel requires R-devel) I also am less inclined to jump between r versions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I am not an expert programmer and while I have developed my own customised scripts I am afraid they might not be sufficient quality</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Not generally relevant to the general population</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Git.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Poor introduction to S4 design</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Time.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Not enough related functions for a coherent package</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The guidline to avoid :: adds busywork and produces packages that load excessive dependencies that may not actually be used. For infrequently used functions, it would be better to indicate the package it is from with :: in the place it is used.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Lacking real examples</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">building and testing on multiple environments. dependency tracking</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Don't have the skills to write one</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">intellectual property, one-off analyses rather than routine work</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Initially many of the standards, as I have a non-programmer background, but after the first round of reviews for my first BioConductor package, I do not see many barriers at all, actually.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Knowledge</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">No barriers per se. Initial review, required good documentation and commitment to maintain the package mean more work, but are essential for good quality packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I am going to do it soon!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Creating data packages for the vignettes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Complexity of release cycle (e.g., need to maintain several concurrent versions of R); self pressure on contributing something bug-free; few unmet needs (for my use) because very large current offer of packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Funding</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">bioconductor doesnt allow dependency on github packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The git/release process was not obvious to me at first.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The package size limitation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">time consuming but it is OK</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Long delays during submission process</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">S4 objects/functions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Guidelines are not easy to fullfil after I had looked at several messages bat the bioc-devel messages and package submission reviews on GitHub, it's obvious that reviewers are requesting changes which often are against guidelines or structure of bioconductor standard classes and tools.
Some of thd "standardised" Bioconductor infrastructure tools and classes are unnecessary complicated and instead of making data processing better make tools to be more prone for ert.
Automated build systems very often are failing and giving random unreproducible fault reports which quite often are related to bugs in syst configuration or Bioconductor infrastructure tools.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Time, code readability (lack of comments, personal coding styles)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">It is time consuming to write proper documentation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">In my opinion, the biggest barrier is the need to learn S4, which is uncommon outside Bioconductor.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Completing my own work</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Time, so not your fault</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">number of potential users, time</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Strict dependencies, i.e., I can't depend on GitHub packages for a Bioconductor package</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The S4 requirements would require a significant rework, and it utilizes non-CRAN/Bioconductor packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Investing time into clean code</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">submission and review process (the rigor is appropriate and documentation is good)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">documentation/test overheads - only useful for code that is useful to many (not Bioconductor specific)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Skill</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Knowledge of S4</td>
    </tr>
  </body>

  <tr>
    <th class="gt_col_heading gt_columns_bottom_border gt_columns_top_border gt_left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Please tell us about your experience with Bioconductor annotation resources (e.g. annotation packages, biomaRt, AnnotationHub, ...)</th>

  <body class="gt_table_body">
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I haven't had any problems so far.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The ability to use specific ensembl releases in biomaRt is really good. I tend not to use annotation sources if I can't bind them to a specific release.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I used to use biomaRt a lot, but then moved on to org*db packages. I haven't use AnnotationHub much yet.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">It's easy to get and handle data coming from Bioconductor annotation resources.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">They are sufficient such that I can do my job more quickly and reliably.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Don't use</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I struggled to find out how to use / develop for it</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">great</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I have very little experience with those.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Great once you get the hang of it but same problem as every bioconductor package: too many classes to keep track of.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Very easy to use. But it is difficult to convert all alias to entriz id.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Good experience with annotation packages (BSgenome, etc). <div id="dpqxvaahcf" style="overflow-x:auto;overflow-y:auto;width:auto;height:auto;"><table class="gt_table">
  
  <tr>
    <th class="gt_col_heading gt_columns_bottom_border gt_columns_top_border gt_left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">What are the best aspects of Bioconductor?</th>
  </tr>
  <body class="gt_table_body">
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">package documentation, high-standard review process.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Great core packages, wide range of packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">load packages, manage dependencies, documentation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Biostrings</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">First, the community. Second, technical aspects: fixed releases ensure all packages work and work well together, packages are (usually) well documented; use of standard data data containers ensure interoperability and ease of use of results generated by new packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">High performance, great maintenance</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">friendly community lower code duplication and increases interoperability</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">open community, long term maintenance and support from developers</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Friendly community; openness; package and code submissions are appreciated by Bioconductor.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Overwhelmingly comprehensive resource, interoperable packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The vignettes in a workflow style, giving people an easy-to-go immediate manual.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Easy to install,good quality,stay updated</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The easy of distribution and the use of vignettes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">community. workshops.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Deseq2 support</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">documentation and compatibility between packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Not just function documentation, but the vignettes. The community.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The established classes (ExpressionSet, DGEList, etc)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Vignettes! And documentation in general. Also, the community is always very helpful in forums, emails, etc. Definitely improved over R-help/R-devel.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Things just work, I never seem to have version/dependencies conflicts; one finds good documentation; there's often good inter-operability</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Interoperability</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Modularity, interoperability, and being open source</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">High-quality review of bioinformatics software and resource for multiple R packages for different aspects</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Community and package system</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Community, higher documentation standards, efforts for standardization</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Packages are generally very good, well maintained, authors are able to be reached</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The community. People generally want to help you use their package effectively.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The review of the packages at the submission is very good. I learn a lot of looking into them. Perhaps it could be further improved asking feedback of domain experts through slack or other official channels.
Forcing to have at least one vignette improves user experience a lot.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The open source nature of the project and the community around the project are awsome.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Statistics and graphs</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">commitment to open-access, interoperability</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Community, knowledge sharing</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">breadth of available packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Number of available tools, ease of installation, documentation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Common data structures. Good documentation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">dependency downloading</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">minimal level of software quality and support, single source/repository with broad collection of tools</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">It makes very high-level analysis possible</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">responsive community, strive to make things easier and more accessible</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">the community!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Lots of packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Good community, active development and community involvement</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">community + community standards, documentation, code stability, ...</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Vignettes, wide range of excellent methods, great community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Shared API across inherited classes, E.g. [</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">the SCE class &amp; how many/most single cell packages easily interact with it.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">package review process</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The base packages are excellent, and the overall quality of user-contributed packages is quite good.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The support and the tutorials</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The best aspect is that most of (not all!) packages have a clear tutorial which allows users to understand how each function works.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Interoperability between (most) packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Open source community and cutting edge.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">It's a great dependency manager, coding standards are pretty helpful to ensure developers can make the most of other packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">IRanges</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">class system, structured inheritance possible</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">cutting-edge, open-source, community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">It is great to have a place where all things biological R are collected on the internet. I really like some core bioconductor classes.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I like the generics and the methods for GRanges, TxDb, EnsDb, and sometimes DNAStringSet that have consistent user interface. I also like the strict requirements for documentation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">package managment</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The Bioconductor community is great. I enjoy being able to identify with a group of like-minded individuals.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Generally, it helps to increase the reliability in bioinformatics software. In the field of bioinformatics, Bioconductor is un-matched in what it does. I long for the day when people can no longer just put random, un-tested code online.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Centralised repository of R packages for bioinformatics</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">the community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Quality of software and the breadth of things you can learn from the support forum. Vignettes, too</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Every package has a vignette, and S4 class</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Vignetters and course information and workflows.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Breadth of Bioconductor packages and training course. Huge community, easy to find help</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Well crafted code</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Community of users, breadth of packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Nice community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Everyone is approachable! Fast response to questions in the forum.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">central location for nearly all bioinformatics R packages, good documentation, good standards for inspection/curation of incoming packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">free, easy to access</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">required vignettes, package review process, CI build checks across platforms</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Great leadership, great community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Documentation, continuous testing, core classes, interoperability of packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The fact that many of the packages integrate so well.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The documentation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">open and friendly community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Its staff</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Robustness.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Having a dedicated platform. Standardization of data formats.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Regularly updated; great in-depth documentation; support site; variety of tools; consistent object types;</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>

<div id="fqkamfvfpa" style="overflow-x:auto;overflow-y:auto;width:auto;height:auto;"><table class="gt_table">
  
  <tr>
    <th class="gt_col_heading gt_columns_bottom_border gt_columns_top_border gt_left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">What are the worst aspects of Bioconductor?</th>
  </tr>
  <body class="gt_table_body">
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">S4.  S4 makes Bioconductor incompatible with most non-bioconductor packages, leading to wasted effort (poorly) duplicating non-bioconductor functionality in bioconductor (e.g ggbio,plyranges)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Some "minor" packages are not easy to understand. The Bioconductor object formats are not always easy to understand.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Sometimes frustrating that nothing stays the same over versions; scripts almost always need updating (might be unavoidable, the field is moving fast too)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Too many tools (very often redundant)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The community was quite closed a few years ago, it has improved a lot.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Data formats and exploration of objects is very counter intuitive if you learned R and the Tidyverse before going into Bioconductor</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">steep learning curve, due to large number of packages it takes effort to find the most appropriate package for analysis</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Hacking at ESets to easily use ggplot2; the duplicate packages; those packages that auto-install other bioconductor packages (this plays hell with my conda envs); `AnnotationDbi::select` vs `dplyr::select` collisions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Sometimes Bioconductor can be quite insular. I love the concept of S4Vectors for example, but they don't tend to play nice with for example tidyverse packages or other neat packages on CRAN (e.g. data.table) that are outside Bioconductor.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Dependencies of the packages, unstable version of packages... sometimes are incompatible with diff version of R.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">too many packages, maybe there should be some kind of filter??</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">When a function gets deprecated</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Finding out the required non-bioconductor dependencies can sometimes be a pain.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">DataFrame and tidyverse-non compatibility, the Bioconductor website</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">tech debt in some project areas (website most notably)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">That I have to update R to often.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">dependency building</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Sometimes trying to get everyone to use the same infrastructure (ie common classes) might be overly restrictive, especially if the Bioc class is not as efficient as some non-Bioc options</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">lack of overview.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I wish that the requirements for unit testing are more stringent. Also, though I have tried SingleCellExperiment, I still prefer Seurat, which is not a Bioconductor package, but I do wish that Seurat has better function documentation. Also, the vignette requirement and time limit for R CMD check are somewhat annoying since I have to limit the vignette to small toy datasets. Since single cell data is getting larger, I put vignettes demonstrating analysis of normal sized scRNA-seq on a stand alone website so I can take my time to rerun them if needed.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Website. Documentation on its Bioconductor S4 classes is poor.  These are often bundled  SummarizedExperiment points to RangedSummarizedExperiment.  IRanges, Granges.   Please make youtube guides and link in vignettes for the main classes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">variable quality of software/usability/documentation; inter-dependencies break code in other packages and create a need for constant updates and maintenance</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The website and the sheer number of classes to keep track of. The website does not allow discover-ability of classes or generics. I also can't see the source code for a package on the Bioconductor website. This would be pretty convenient.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I hated the fact that it took me a long time to be able to use bioconductor successfully. There is probably no way around it, since the packages and the analyses they perform are fairly advanced, but any thing can be done on this front would be useful.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Basing every second release on r-devel</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Obliging packages to use the latest version of R</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">For beginners it is difficult to know where to start</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">difficult to find a package, packages need to be ordered better on the site</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">version of packages not linked to version of Bioconductor</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Poor maintenance of core packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Some packages have really poor documentation! Most are good, because of the Bioconductor review process. However some have poor docs, maybe because a lot of new functionality was added after acceptance</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Package discovery</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">S4 generics. Interaction of Bioconductor with tidyverse</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Optimization of core packages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">too many packages have overlapping functionalities (or are redundant)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">6-monthly devel/master cycle can sometimes be inconvenient</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">It is difficult to get tutorials about how to use the programs, particular about the formats used to get in the programs, when the data is raw, not already in R.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Limited use of tidyverse approaches</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Documentation of some packages can be out of date</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Documentation is often spotty and confusing. Especially in the user-contributed packages, but also in the core Bioconductor packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">It is hard to et help or see code for S4 methods/classes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">S4 Class complexity</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Redundant information across the website for developers; e.g. the developer resources at https://bioconductor.org/developers are spread across many articles and should be re-written to be simpler and with less redundancy</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Leaving package documentation up to package authors is always a bit dicey.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Packages changing without notification</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">None</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Bioconductor tends to duplicate efforts (some packages have their parallels in CRAN, like the BiocParallel and parallel, or future). This makes harder to learn about packages and uses and makes feel that Bioconductor is aside the large R community. 
Also, once a package is approved the authors can introduce changes without review, which sometimes is abused to introduce methods that wouldn't get through review.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">high start-up cost for prospective developers makes it kind of an exclusive club</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">documentation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Three aspects. First, there is not a standard, concerning the manual creation; some manuals are very precise and comprehensive, while others are too much bare and simplistic. Second, the website is not use-friendly, especially for a new-user. Finally, as a developer I'm interested in more information about my packages, not only the number of downloads (e.g., the Countries where the package is downloaded; if the package is downloaded by a Bioconductor developer or a simple user; ...)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Trying to imitate Java.

Load time of some core packages seems unnecessarily high, and also produces verbose messages.

DataFrame type doesn't play well with Tidyverse.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The website is confusing at times, and it's not always easy to find the resources, e.g., help with git for maintaining packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">there is no good overview of the overall packages and functionalities, very often the same functionality is written in different packages in different manners.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">the density of the documentation (probably unavoidable given BioC's breadth)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">finding useful docs through website.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The community. People can be dismissive of non-Bioconductor packages for seemingly no reason. New contributors may not find themselves up to snuff for many Bioc devs - code reviews can be harsh. It's not a place many beginner-intermediate R users will be tempted to try to contribute to. This isn't really a Bioconductor thing though, more just a result of many of the devs contributing to it being experts and having high standards (which isn't a bad thing).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">the updates that break backwards compatibility. Requires a lot of time to depend on bioconductor packages because things break every bioconductor update...</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Constant update of packages. It was easier to maintain workflow when changes where pushed only twice a year.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">That some packages are not as integrated as they could be. It would be great if integrating to core structures would be even more strictly enforced, so that the flow from package to package would be seamless.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">small community can feel cliquish (around labs/institutes/twitter activity)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Finding packages, vignettes are hit-or-miss</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">some lack of standardization, due to packages coming from many sources.  In some cases, too many layers of abstraction make it hard to understand what the underlying data structures are really doing.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Old package with weird code base</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">hmm, there were surprising changes in system-level dependencies</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">S4 classes are somewhat cumbersome to write.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">There can be large difference in the quality of packages. Coding styles can be very different and make some packages difficult to use, understand, or debug.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">unstructured universe of packages, little training (it's good time to have MOOCs, e.g. on DataCamp for core packages).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Very poor guides on core S4 system.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">needs to become more diverse in terms of gender and under-represented minorities in the community and eventually to leadership roles</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Complicated infrastructure classes. Unnecessary limiting code guidelines. E.g. 50 line function length, ignoring power of R core functionality.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Ease for reproducing analysis (e.g., how to rerun an analysis with specific versions of packages); working with release and devel packages at same time</td>
    </tr>
  </body>
  
  
</table></div>

  <tr>
    <th class="gt_col_heading gt_columns_bottom_border gt_columns_top_border gt_left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Do you have suggestions for new activities to benefit the user or developer community?</th>

    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Hackhathon to encourage interaction between package developers (and interested users), to promote understanding and contribution to packages by new or existing developers.</td>

    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">no</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The submission and review process is great. I just don't understand why the packages are not hosted on GitHub directly! Maybe there is a technical reasons for it but models line the ROpenSci are working, so why not. I also think the developers mailing list can be improved. Maybe it's my email client, but I can't follow the conversations and there is no way to show code and messages properly. Maybe a slack channel!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">A better overview of common S4 object classes (update and expand http://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/S4Vectors/inst/doc/S4QuickOverview.pdf)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Better S4 tutorials, especially extending core S4 classes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Not really. I'm not aware that bioconductor does much community outreach. It would be nice to have a disqus-type comments section at the end of the workflow pages</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Referred to the previous comment "packages overview": there should be better uniformity between the packages.
1. Giving to the developers a unique repository of available packages and functions. (in such a way no-one reinvents the wheel). This can be useful for package reviewers and for developers.
2. If a new function is proposed with the same "aim" of an existing one (in another package), it'd be useful to highlight the why and how it is "better" than the existing one.
In case it is really better than the old one, three possible approaches:
2.1 substitute the existing function with the new one
2.2 implement the "better" aspects in the old function
2.3 release the new function in the new package, printing a info message on the existing of the old functions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">More tutorials maybe (please not using video!); dedicated team in charge of optimizing slow packages;  dedicated team in charge of (re)implementing packages of methods used in one field but not available in R (e.g., I really appreciated the reimplementation of SingleR)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">It would be nice to have a recurrent screencast (monthly?) through youtube or similar, in which Marin or some other core member shows what's new in Bioconductor. Sometimes it is hard to update your pipeline with the latest packages and/or best practices.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">More of the bookdown style tutorials like "orchestrating single cell", but they need to be updated more often / benchmarked against competing tools.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Give more training how to build packages. Once you lear how to compile and build, you understand much better how to use the packages and how to ask for help.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">not really, maybe community hackatons to fill in feature gaps?</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">hackathon-like' events for students to create useful packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Create wordles or even better text clustering of package descriptions. Embed bioschemas and/or make authors improve annotation of packages in bio.tools</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">More workflows such as F1000 and highlighting strategies that have non-standard analyses to provide some intuition of extensions of methods that are useful.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Expand the community beyond RNASeq and cancer</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">There needs to be an standardised guide /tutorials to use each library. Not only with data from the creators. Many times when you try to use your own data it does not work or it is not clear because the authors simply used a function on their built-in data and the results are not extrapolated.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">More intermediate to advanced workshops. There is a gap between beginner/easy and advanced courses.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">More workflows and more training</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">More Datathons</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Not an activity really- but a package primer/vignette on 10 key things when developing a Bioc package or similar would we useful for new developers to ease their entry into the Bioc developer world.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">One thing that I think would be a great quality increase (even if I understand that that would need many more of the developers to engage in reviewing) would be that each package would undergo re-review every two years, or something like this. Otherwise it is possible to get the package into BioConductor, and then starting to slip from the standards.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">don't assume we have root or sudo, I use R so I can run scripts, but so many packages assume I can update Python and Fortran and it's impossible</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Structured and inaccessible guide to develop bioconductor packages.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">The availability of tutorials but going beyond the use of humans and data already in R.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">I wish Bioconductor would have more transparent development. I'd like to know what development is going on and other news in packages I'm interested in, in the same way I could go to the ggplot2 github package and follow the discussion there so I may learn about the reasoning behind certain decisions. For example, I still don't understand why I can't lapply over a GRanges object anymore.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I like the F1000 Bioconductor workflows (i also use them for teaching), so please keep this going. Another suggestion: better indicate the number of downloads of a package because this can serve for new users as indicator which package is popular and should be considered essential.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The organization of specific workshops/schools/meetings, led by groups of Bioconductor developers, to face specific tasks: one dedicated to machine learning, one to deep learning, one to RNA-Seq analysis, one to SNP identification, and so on.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Not that I found.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Don't require all new packagws to use bioconductor infrastructure tools if there is no need.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Package developer introduction book (like http://r-pkgs.had.co.nz/) with focus on Bioconductor packages: ie. best practices, pitfalls etc.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Maybe create a slack channel, youtube tutorials</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Meetups/newsletters/blogs of gists/more youtube video /courses (capentry)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">No, I'm sorry.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Re-analyse existing published data comparing choices and tools, data analytic competitions.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Something like the tidyverse developer day could help onboarding new users</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Workshops are always great.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">not exactly new, but I appreciate the local meetup events!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Not really</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Direct participation in things like the NLM/NCBI codeathons/hackathons might be cool.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">not sure -- hackathons seem like just a way to amortize bad technical debt</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">User workflows are good, developer community might benefit from more prominent examples for inheriting, good practices and coding style</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Hack-a-thons, community retreats (un-conf), Bioconductor softball tournament!</td>

    </tr>
    <tr>

    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Would like more training and workflows</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Increased usability of core packages, like a countOverlaps() using score column for hits, etc.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Whatever Seurat can do but SingleCellExperiment based packages can't, such as data integration. But meanwhile, I wish that Seurat can work with HDF5Array for data that can't fit into memory.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Single cell analysis is fragmented over so many packages. https://osca.bioconductor.org/ is a good start, but it is actually too complex. scRNA-seq analysis is pretty much the wild west right now, especially once spatial/Visium come out. I use Seurat because it is both sophisticated yet easy to use, and only occasionally pull in a few BioC functions.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">There are some genomic range operations that are vey easy with bedtools but rather complex with GenmocRanges</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">something like IGV is kind of missing from Bioconductor, current packages are clunky</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Proteomics, tidyverse integration</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Hi-C analysis on bioconductor seem quite sparse.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">I would like to access data on Google Big Query / Table programmatically. It's still an area I need to get familiar with.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">my_dge %&gt;% filter(feature_id %in% some_set) %&gt;% filter(sample_treatment != "undesirable-treatment") %&gt;% ggplot2(aes(x = sample_treatment, y = intensity)) + geom_boxplot()</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">deep learning</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">visualization (Gviz, ggbio but with continued support/development)?</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Would like to have Seurat package that is compatible with SCE objects</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Get easier access to a wide variety of GRanges/bed files from public data (e.g. ChIP-seq experiments). Also, not Bioc specific but in R it is hard to do some dimensionality reduction techniques/matrix factorization with big data (more specifically, I would like to do partial least squares regression with a large number of variables)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">None that I can think of</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Facilitating single-cell genomics benchmark of methods, parameter exploration, using parallel/cloud computing where possible. It is technically possible, but requires more time than any individual scientist or research group really has, I think. Teamwork could facilitate this.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Cross species interactions, especially microbial, equivalent of STRING but across species.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">local support.</td>
    </tr>
  </body>
  
  
</table></div>

<div id="mqjlwrlefp" style="overflow-x:auto;overflow-y:auto;width:auto;height:auto;"><table class="gt_table">
  
  <tr>
    <th class="gt_col_heading gt_columns_bottom_border gt_columns_top_border gt_left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Is there anything else you'd like to tell us? (e.g. future vision for Bioconductor, ...)</th>
  </tr>
  <body class="gt_table_body">
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Keep on rocking!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">no</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">I know some R packages that implement cool ideas that forever remained on GitHub and never made it to Bioconductor. I wonder if the stricter requirements for Bioconductor packages are intimidating to some package authors. It was a lot of work to get my package to fulfill the requirements.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">No</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">At the Bioc meeting, there is a group who all know each other as they all shared PIs. Bioc diversity should ensure it's not dominated by a few PIs, &amp; their postdocs who are now PIs.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">While the contributions from people at places like MIT/Harvard and other ivy league schools has been incredibly helpful and a great service to the Bioc/scientific community (and hopefully will continue), it might be nice to increase involvement from people at other universities. Also, at the latest Bioc conference (2019) I looked around at one point in one of the bigger rooms with a lot of people and I don't recall seeing any African American people. Just an observation. Overall my experience with Bioconductor has been great so thanks to all those who have contributed time and effort!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Not really</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Many thanks for all your work and dedication.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Keep up the great work!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Great resource and software</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">My major concern for the project is sustainability. If the project is to continue, I would hope that it looks past current funding mechanisms and finds alternate revenue streams. For example, Bioconductor can very well provide professional services such as consulting, package / code review, analysis at a cost to companies and individuals.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">very grateful to the Bioconductor community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Keep up the great work - I couldn't do my job without you!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">I wish bioconductor had a bigger emphasis on converting between Bio-specific data formats and generic base R data structures.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">some sort of SimpleBioC intro to the core classes &amp; workflows would be neat</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">The growing number of Bioc packages is sometimes counter productive, especially when users need to try several "bad" packages before finding the "good" one. Perhaps Bioc can afford to be more selective in the packages that it accepts. I find it already a good practice to discontinue packages that are not maintained and systematically fail the nightly builds</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Keep on with the good stuff - you made me a better (working) person by embracing your philosophy and learning from you all.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">It would be very nice if you could announce the release schedule further ahead of time to help us plan.
Currently I think the review process focuses to much on classes, methods etc an less on usability and user friendly documentation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Keep on going with the good work!!!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Keep up the great work</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">It would be nice if there could be curators for each area (RNA, genomics, epigenomics, data visualisation , etc) who could review packages and somehow create a whole integrative tutorial for each area with open access data and using several packages. Perhaps YouTube videos similar to those of Dave Robinson on tidy Tuesday.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Try to normalize the vocabulary and not multiply packages that do the same thing but with different terminolgy, it seems like a waste of resources. More carefully check the statistical correctness of packages, not just computational correctness.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Perhaps writing a guidebook or filming a tutorial about how to use all the Bioconductor resources could help all the users. 
Also some kind of announcement on each release about not only the deprecated packages but new packages and improvements on the existing packages would help to move forward. 
Upon acceptance of a package in Bioconductor it is accepted that the maintainers must be reachable and answer questions about the package however this is rarely enforced or encoded in some way (answers older than 6 months without answers from the maintainer count or should we wait for 6 more months?).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Keep up the great work!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">As Bioconductor continues to standardize around a simple set of types, the userbase will become less and less skilled and also vastly larger. I hope this can continue.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Keep up your great work!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Thank you</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">great work - most valuable to the community and the research field(s) - keep it up!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Improve the website to make it easier to explore packages with a more modern interface</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Thanks, for all the work in creating an awesome community</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Keep up the good work</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Keep up the good work, and thanks for all!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left">Thak you for so many great packages!!</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="gt_row gt_left gt_striped">Keep up the good work! :-) 
One thing: in order to focus resources on new code instead of fixing broken legacy code, I value as much backward compatibility as reasonable and a minimum of breaking changes eg to core packages.  I have been quite happy with BioC in this respect, in contrast to eg certain RStudio pkgs that are otherwise appealing but simply less useful if you have to maintain your analysis code.</td>
    </tr>
  </body>
